I've visited Kampai 2x before my recent visit with great experiences. During this occasion the restaurant was uncomfortably cold. Understandably, it's the winter time and many restaurant blow cold air for a "fast customer turnover". However, in the cold season I would imagine most restaurants would attempt to create a comfortable and cozy dining atmosphere. Most of the patrons left their coats on while dining, and the restroom was far colder. Aside from the atmosphere, I have loved their rolls in the past and am always open to trying a variety of sushi and sashimi at various restaurants. We ordered the squid as an appetizer, which was flavorful, but unbearably chewy. Our dinner choice was the Kampai Combo (BEWARE it is Chefs Choice as if there are some surprising elements to it) hoping that we would be able to try a unique specialty roll from the Chef (as the waitress suggested that we inform of any allergies) only to be highly disappointed by a typical California Roll -_- The salmon, tuna, and yellow tail sashimi were perfect, no complaint. The nigiri shrimp and salmon were excellent. However, the nigiri tuna was so overly spiced that neither of us wanted to finish it after the first bite. I would normally recommend Kampai to our friends. This time we were quite disappointed with our sub-par/subzero experience and may give it another chance in the spring when it's warmer. We most likely not be return customers though.

The wait staff was courteous. Ultimately, I would go back.

I recently moved back to St. Louis and am on the hunt for a new sushi restaurant to haunt. This is the first sushi place we've tried that I was delightfully pleased with. We tried several things. We got the Takoyaki which I really enjoyed. My husband thought it was a little mushy, but that's kind of just how the dish is. We got the Joy roll which was pretty good, but the torching process left a sort of burnt taste. We also got the Vegas roll which was good. I definitely want to try their other rolls. We also got some nigiri: masago, seared tuna, and uni. All were great, but make sure you try uni in your lifetime. SO GOOD! We'll definitely come back, but are still on the hunt for a place with more interesting rolls. The service here was outstanding. Only downside is there's no parking lot, only street parking.

They are some localized, Americanized variation of sushi which in no ways reflect the restaurant authenticity and the true quality of the the sushi. Sushi is alright, but definitely over priced. The same price I can get much better quality sushi other places. It is probably true that it is good in CWE, but mediocre in the broader region of STL.

With that price I can have x1000 better quality sushi in any asian quality. The taste was not much better than panda express sushi. they charged +20% tips for nothing, they don't even fill my glass. For spice rolls, they just use some chinese hot sauce on the regular salmon rolls.

Beyond question, the WORST sushi I have ever eaten, and I've been eating sushi since the early 1970s.  Small pieces of NOT fresh fish on tiny balls of rice.   Not only did it taste off, it had a slimy texture.   Eeeeeeuuuugh.   SO not good.  Greasy, tasteless tempura with a bland dipping sauce.  Even the seaweed salad tasted off.  I would NEVER go back and would NEVER recommend the place.

I can't actually comment on the atmosphere and decor, because I ordered delivery from them a couple times rather than dining in. I called them up on my way home and asked if they deliver sushi or only the standard entrees. Of course, much to my delight, they deliver everything on the menu! It was about $60 for two people to order 5 rolls, but it was well worth it. The sushi was fantastic and the service was excellent. I've been to most of the sushi places in St. Louis, and Kampai definitely ranks up there with the best like Fin and Oishi. Much better than Drunken Fish that's right down the street. If you like eating in a loud hipster restaurant with all undergrads drinking fruity drinks then by all means hit up the Drunken Fish. If you want good Sushi in the CWE, try Kampai!

There are a ton of sushi restaurants in the CWE, but Kampai is by far my favorite.  It doesn't have the fanciest "fusion" rolls (Sub-Zero), nor does it serve crazy martinis that sound Japanese (Drunken Fish.)  What it does have is simple: authentic sushi with quality fish at very reasonable prices.  Where else can you get a large bowl of Chirashi with good quality, large cuts of sashimi including miso and salad for $10 (lunch special) ?  Heck, this alone brought me back at least twice a week. With their rolls, they stick mostly to the classics, and they do them well.  Good selection of Japanese beer and sake, but this is first and foremost a sushi stop.  I have since moved from St. Louis and miss this place terribly.  I have eaten in more sushi places than I can count, but Kampai always holds a place dear to my heart.
In my opinion this is the best sushi in St. Louis.  Everything on the menu is incredible.  Enough said.
